Problem 1: Bike Sharing Dataset

This data set collects the bike sharing counts aggregated on daily basis (2011-2012) together with the calender information (year/season/weekday/holiday) and daily weather conditions. There are 4 weather realted variables:

  • weathersit: (GOOD, MISTY, RAIN/SNOW/STORM)

  • temperature (in Celsius)

  • humidity (relative to 100%)

  • windspeed

The objective is to predict the bike sharing counts given a date, and figure out the impacts on the counts due to weather conditions.

Your analysis should include the following:

  • EDA and preliminary findings.

  • Fit tree-based models and summarize their prediction performance. The tuning parameters for tree-based models should be determined via cross validation.

  • Fit a linear regression and a nonlinear regression model for the target variable count. Again, your models should go through a proper model selection procedure. Summarize the selected models with their prediction performance.

  • Identify the important input variables for predicting bike sharing counts. In particular, characterize the effects of weather conditions on the bike counts quantitatively.

  • Give a brief analysis summary.

Data Structure Adjustment

First, convert categorical variables into factor. As for the year variable, since there are only two value in that column, so we decide to turn it into factor, too.

bike$season<-factor(bike$season)
bike$year<-factor(bike$year)
bike$month<-factor(bike$month)
bike$holiday<-factor(bike$holiday)
bike$weekday<-factor(bike$weekday)
bike$workingday<-factor(bike$workingday)
bike$weather<-factor(bike$weather)

Since the meaning of “holiday” and “working” columns are a little bit ambiguous; therefore, we create a new column called “special day” that covers all range of day type. Class1-“WORKING DAY”: workingday=1, holiday=0 Class2-“HOLIDAY”: workingday=0, holiday=1 Class3-“WEEKEND”: workingday=0, holiday=0

bike$specialday[bike$holiday=="HOLIDAY"]<-"HOLIDAY"
bike$specialday[bike$workingday=="WORKING DAY"]<-"WORKING DAY"
bike$specialday[(bike$holiday=="NO HOLIDAY")&(bike$workingday=="NO WORKING DAY")]<-"WEEKEND"
bike$specialday<-factor(bike$specialday)

pairs(bike[,c("temp","hum", "windspeed",    "count")])

Decide a new dataframe

By the above description, we can know that compare to “weekday” and “month”, “special day” and “season” seem to be more interpretable. Therefore, we finally choose “year”, “season”, “specialday”, “weather”, “temp”, “hum”, “windspeed” to be the predictors of final dataframe.

bike_new<-bike[,c("year","season","specialday","weather","temp","hum","windspeed","count")]

Model1: Tree

The first model is decision tree, we fit it into the training set, and visualize it.

tree.bike <- tree(count ~ ., bike.tr)
summary(tree.bike)
## 
## Regression tree:
## tree(formula = count ~ ., data = bike.tr)
## Variables actually used in tree construction:
## [1] "temp"   "year"   "season" "hum"   
## Number of terminal nodes:  9 
## Residual mean deviance:  739600 = 425300000 / 575 
## Distribution of residuals:
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## -4269.0  -477.7   118.0     0.0   566.6  2782.0
plot(tree.bike);text(tree.bike,pretty = 0)

By the above tree, the most important indicator for bike sharing count appears to be “temperature”, and “year” plays an important role in both parts. We can clearly see that bike count in year 2012 is significantly higher than year2011. As for the following nodes, we can generally observe the effect caused by “season” and “humidity”, in spring or winter season, people rent less bike; and in high humidity weather condition, people rent less.

cv.bike <- cv.tree(tree.bike)
plot(cv.bike$size, cv.bike$dev, type = "b")

By the cross validation plot, we can see that the deviation of tree starts to converge at tree size=6; therefore, we pick 6 as the best tree size.

Then we prune the tree based on the best size and visualize it.

prune.bike <- prune.tree(tree.bike, best = 6)
plot(prune.bike);text(prune.bike, pretty = 0)

As we mentioned before, we still can see effect caused by indicators such as temperature, year, season, while humidity seems to be less important after the tree was pruned.

Make predictions based on decision tree and see the distribution of y_hat and true value of bike sharing count.

yhat <- predict(prune.bike, newdata = bike.tst)
plot(yhat, bike.tst$count);abline(0, 1)

Calculate MSE of decision tree.

MSE_tree<-mean((yhat - bike.tst$count)^2)
MSE_tree
## [1] 937345.1

Model2: Random Forest & Bagging

The second model is random forest and bagging, and decide the best parameter by 5-fold cross validation. #### Random Forest Fit random forest model and view the cv error list.

k <- 5
n <- nrow(bike.tr)
set.seed(1)
folds <- sample(rep(1:k, length = n))
cv.errors <- matrix(NA, k, 8, dimnames = list(NULL, paste(1:8)))
for (j in 1:k) {
  for (i in 1:8) {
  best.fit<-randomForest(count ~ ., data = bike.tr[folds != j,] ,mtry = i, importance=TRUE)
  pred <- predict(best.fit, bike.tr[folds == j, ])
cv.errors[j, i] <- mean((bike.tr$count[folds == j] - pred)^2)
}
}
mean.cv.errors <- apply(cv.errors, 2, mean)
mean.cv.errors
##        1        2        3        4        5        6        7        8 
## 836897.6 488798.3 470669.4 487226.4 494866.9 511806.9 522453.3 520649.0
which.min(mean.cv.errors)
## 3 
## 3
plot(mean.cv.errors, type = "b");points(8, mean.cv.errors[8], col = "red", cex = 1.5, pch = 20)

By the above plot, we can see that cv errors converge after mtry=5, and the min value happens at 8, so we choose 5 as the best mtry size.

Best random forest model

Then, we fit the best mtry value selected by k-fold cross validation into random forest model, and make prediction on test set.

yhat.ran <- predict(bike.ran, newdata = bike.tst)

The above graph shows the distribution of predicted y_hat and true value of bike sharing count. Compared to decision tree, we can see that relationship between y_hat and real count value fits the line with slope=1 better.

Model3: Boosting

The next tree model comes to boosting. Similarly, using 5-fold to decide the best parameter of boosting model.

k <- 5
n <- nrow(bike.tr)
set.seed(1)
folds <- sample(rep(1:k, length = n))
cv.errors <- matrix(NA, k, 5, dimnames = list(NULL, paste(1:5)))
for (j in 1:k) {
  for (i in 1:5) {
  best.fit <- gbm(count ~ ., data =bike.tr[folds!=j,],
    distribution = "gaussian", n.trees = 1000,
    interaction.depth = 5,shrinkage = i*0.01)
  pred <- predict(best.fit, bike.tr[folds == j, ])
cv.errors[j, i] <- mean((bike.tr$count[folds == j] - pred)^2)
}
}
mean.cv.errors <- apply(cv.errors, 2, mean)

Model4: Linear Regression

First, fit linear regression into all variables,and calculate its MSE.

#Regression with all variable
bike.lm<-lm(count~.,data=bike.tr)
yhat.reg<-predict(bike.lm,bike.tst)
MSE_reg<-mean((yhat.reg - bike.tst$count)^2)
MSE_reg
## [1] 779868.5

The MSE of regression model with all variables don’t seem to have ideal performance compared to the above tree based model. Hence, we’ll do some adjustments in the following steps.

First, define a prediction function to make prediction based on forward selection

predict.regsubsets <- function(object, newdata, id, ...) {
  form <- as.formula(object$call[[2]])
  mat <- model.matrix(form, newdata)
  coefi <- coef(object, id = id)
  xvars <- names(coefi)
  mat[, xvars] %*% coefi
 }

Pick forward selection as the variable selection method, and use 5-fold cross validation to select the best variable set.

k <- 5
n <- nrow(bike.tr)
set.seed(1)
folds <- sample(rep(1:k, length = n))
cv.errors <- matrix(NA, k, 8, dimnames = list(NULL, paste(1:8)))

for (j in 1:k) {
best.fit <- regsubsets(count ~ ., data = bike.tr[folds != j, ], nvmax = 8
, method = "forward")
for (i in 1:8) {
pred <- predict(best.fit, bike.tr[folds == j, ], id = i)
cv.errors[j, i] <- mean((bike.tr$count[folds == j] - pred)^2)
}
}
mean.cv.errors <- apply(cv.errors, 2, mean)
mean.cv.errors
##         1         2         3         4         5         6         7         8 
## 2243295.2 1166502.5  944763.5  833462.1  749131.7  711653.0  713616.8  702563.6
which.min(mean.cv.errors)
## 8 
## 8
plot(mean.cv.errors, type = "b");points(8, mean.cv.errors[8], col = "red", cex = 1.5, pch = 20)

From the above graph, we can see that cv error starts to converge after id=5, and reach minimum when id=8; therefore, we choose 5 as the best id number.

Fit the best id number into linear regression.

Take a deeper look at coefficients of the linear regression with best performance. For the “weather” variable, it turns out that the class “MISTY” and “RAIN/SNOW/STORM” appear to be significant in the regression model. They both cause negative effect to the bike sharing count, and the effect caused by “RAIN/SNOW/STORM” is more severe based on the amount of coefficient. As for other weather related variables such as temperature, humidity, windspeed, most of them have negative effect on the target variable as they increase. It is worth to mention that only coefficient of poly(temp, 3)1 is positive, and the we speculate reason behind is that bike sharing count increase as temperature increase originally, while as temperature reaches certain level, the bike demand starts to drop, which has been shown on the dependence plots for “temp” variable.

To conclude, for the model performance, tree based model such as random forest and boosting share similar MSE, and the regression model performs not well when it’s linear, while after adding some nonlinear terms, the model performance can reach that of tree based model.

Method 1: Lasso

Create dataframe for lasso.

y <- survey1.tr$satisfaction
x <- data.matrix(survey1.tr[, -23])

Fit lasso regression into training set and select the best lambda value by cross validation(k=10) for the final model.

# Find the best lambda using cross-validation
cv.lasso <- cv.glmnet(x, y, alpha = 1,family = "binomial")
plot(cv.lasso)

# Fit the final model on the training data
survey1.lasso <- glmnet(x, y, alpha = 1, family = "binomial",
                lambda = cv.lasso$lambda.min)

Make predictions by lasso model on the test data.

x.test <- data.matrix(survey1.tst[, -23])
probabilities <- predict(survey1.lasso,newx = x.test)
yhat.lasso <- ifelse(probabilities > 0.5, 1, 0)

Method 2: Random Forest

We choose random forest as the second model, and use tuning function in random forest package to select the best mtry value.

Conclusion: important aspects of the flight experience

To identify the important aspects of the flight experience related to customer satisfaction, let’s summarize the variable importance for the two models.

For the lasso regression model, “Customer.Type” and “Type.of.Travel” may be the factors that is worth evaluating if the company wants to improve the customer satisfaction. Since the two variables are mainly about the information of customers themselves; for this reason, the company could try to some provide customized services for different types of customers against their need.

As for random forest model, “Customer.Type” and “Type.of.Travel” also holds certain level of importance, and we additionally take “Online.boarding”, “Inflight.wifi.service”, “Checkin.service” such variables into consideration. That means customers really care about convenience of process related to check-in and boarding, and inflight wifi service is required for them to. In general, from the above descriptions, we can know that customers may pay attention the efficiency for the whole journey, and we can speculate that most of them are probably on business trip.

To conclude, customized services and improvement of convenience for the whole flight experience may be suggestions for achieving a higher customer satisfaction.
